1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:10,580
I was rooting around the websites and I came across a course that was written by a man called

2
00:00:12,198 --> 00:00:13,058
Andrew Olenski.

3
00:00:13,339 --> 00:00:24,457
So he was the director of the Barry Center for Buddhist Studies, which is an offshoot from IMS, which is the big meditation center in Barry, Massachusetts.

4
00:00:25,160 --> 00:00:33,192
That was begun by Joseph Goldstein, Sharon Salzberg, Jack Cornfield, some of you know, and lots of others, too.

5
00:00:34,692 --> 00:00:38,776
So he did a lot of good work while he was there and they produce a very good magazine.

6
00:00:38,835 --> 00:00:50,649
Anyway, he's done a course based on the Karaniyameta Sutta, which is what we normally go through at the end of this sitting.

7
00:00:51,029 --> 00:00:56,734
So I thought I'd just go through it to give you an idea of how the Buddha puts it all together.

8
00:00:56,774 --> 00:01:03,061
And then if you want, I'll put the link for that course if you want to take it a bit further.

9
00:01:05,471 --> 00:01:06,100
Okay.

10
00:01:09,099 --> 00:01:38,905
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambodasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambodasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambodasa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble and fully Self-Awakened One.

11
00:01:40,740 --> 00:01:49,856
Yeah, just in case I forget at the end, I hope you have a joyful Christmas and a great new year.

12
00:01:51,777 --> 00:01:53,780
I usually forget to say those sort of things.

13
00:01:54,501 --> 00:02:01,373
Okay, so the Karaniya Metta Sutta is the discourse on what we ought to do in order to develop metta.

14
00:02:01,412 --> 00:02:02,515
That's what Karaniya means.

15
00:02:02,975 --> 00:02:09,687
And it comes from a very early strata of the Buddha's teachings, which was a collection of verses.

16
00:02:09,787 --> 00:02:12,572
So remember that in those days, they couldn't read and write.

17
00:02:13,152 --> 00:02:16,418
It's a bit odd to think of the Buddha as an illiterate, but he was.

18
00:02:16,987 --> 00:02:27,957
And therefore, because it was written as a verse, it's pretty close to what he himself would have developed, you see.

19
00:02:28,658 --> 00:02:32,301
So that word metta comes from the word mitta, which means friends.

20
00:02:33,362 --> 00:02:40,590
Now, to translate metta, we can use the words that you'll see, this loving kindness.

21
00:02:40,750 --> 00:02:46,115
So loving is the attitude that you have within yourself and kindness is the way you express it.

22
00:02:46,194 --> 00:02:46,455
Yeah.

23
00:02:48,663 --> 00:02:52,168
There's another one called goodwill.

24
00:02:52,549 --> 00:02:57,836
See, that stresses the role of intention and the will itself.

25
00:02:57,855 --> 00:03:00,038
And of course, it's in the Christmas greeting, isn't it?

26
00:03:00,620 --> 00:03:04,925
Peace on earth and goodwill to all men, or as we would say, all sentient beings.

27
00:03:06,788 --> 00:03:13,117
Bhikkhu Bodhi's definition is a heartfelt concern for the well-being and happiness of others.

28
00:03:13,384 --> 00:03:16,210
I think that sort of touches a bit on compassion, really.

29
00:03:16,950 --> 00:03:22,221
And it doesn't really mention that there's no self-interest and there's no attachment.

30
00:03:22,681 --> 00:03:29,473
So we've got lots of types of love, erotic, romantic, family relationships, friends, people at work.

31
00:03:31,137 --> 00:03:32,759
Now, those aren't evil relationships.

32
00:03:34,512 --> 00:03:38,355
You would still have those relationships, even if you were fully liberated.

33
00:03:38,455 --> 00:03:43,639
But unfortunately, because we're not liberated, there'll be some attachment to them.

34
00:03:43,680 --> 00:03:50,126
There'll be some expectations of them, which leads to disappointment and sometimes to control.

35
00:03:50,186 --> 00:03:56,231
So that's all to do with the type of unwholesome love.

36
00:03:56,252 --> 00:04:02,798
Now, Buddha Gosa, who was this writer of the Path of Purification, some of you might know, it's a great big tome, which is

37
00:04:03,283 --> 00:04:08,955
probably one of the great spiritual manuals of the world in the fifth century.

38
00:04:08,995 --> 00:04:10,598
This was his definition.

39
00:04:10,657 --> 00:04:13,502
This is how he defined all virtues.

40
00:04:14,145 --> 00:04:20,295
Metta has the mode of friendliness as its characteristic.

41
00:04:20,315 --> 00:04:23,401
Its natural function is to promote friendliness.

42
00:04:25,086 --> 00:04:29,074
It is manifested as the disappearance of ill will.

43
00:04:29,334 --> 00:04:30,276
That's a bit odd, isn't it?

44
00:04:30,317 --> 00:04:31,980
To manifest something that disappears.

45
00:04:32,641 --> 00:04:37,449
But it's basically when there's no ill will, you know that it's got to be meta.

46
00:04:38,271 --> 00:04:43,180
And its footing, its basis is seeing with kindness.

47
00:04:44,290 --> 00:04:45,952
Now, here's a line which I like.

48
00:04:46,353 --> 00:04:53,184
When it succeeds, it eliminates ill will, because you can't have those two mental states together, right?

49
00:04:53,363 --> 00:04:55,487
If you've got good will, there can't be ill will there.

50
00:04:56,509 --> 00:05:01,437
When it fails, it degenerates into selfish, affectionate desire.

51
00:05:02,678 --> 00:05:04,380
Those are a couple of strong lines there.

52
00:05:05,923 --> 00:05:12,052
And metta, of course, appears quite often in the Buddha's lists, these interminable lists.

53
00:05:12,353 --> 00:05:13,795
It's one of the perfections.

54
00:05:14,536 --> 00:05:19,300
It's one of the divine abodes, which is the most beautiful mental state that you can develop.

55
00:05:20,281 --> 00:05:24,266
It's one of the four illimitables with compassion, joy, and equanimity.

56
00:05:24,286 --> 00:05:27,591
It means that you can just develop it indefinitely, right?

57
00:05:29,153 --> 00:05:34,538
And it's also a suitable subject to develop these absorptions, these sort of blissed-out states.

58
00:05:35,379 --> 00:05:37,702
Okay, so the first stanza says,

59
00:05:38,915 --> 00:05:41,478
This is what has to be done.

60
00:05:41,538 --> 00:05:46,862
One has to be skilled in what is good in order to reach the peaceful state.

61
00:05:47,884 --> 00:05:51,749
Okay, Santampadam, the path of peacefulness.

62
00:05:52,149 --> 00:06:03,120
Now, this is about achieving Nirvana, but you'll find if you do that course that he sort of stretches it into peace in society, peace within yourself and all that.

63
00:06:03,161 --> 00:06:07,925
But it's actually, this discourse is actually about achieving Nirvana.

64
00:06:11,702 --> 00:06:23,516
But it is worthwhile to notice when you're peaceful because that quality opacity is a quality of the seven factors of enlightenment.

65
00:06:23,576 --> 00:06:27,466
It's one of those things that we ought to develop just generally, you know.

66
00:06:30,096 --> 00:06:36,303
So these are the things that we have, in a sense, he's presuming that we've developed a little bit.

67
00:06:36,843 --> 00:06:43,170
The first one is sako, which means a confidence, a capability in doing this sort of work.

68
00:06:44,372 --> 00:06:50,899
And we'll end up by suggesting one way that we can do that.

69
00:06:52,079 --> 00:06:58,026
The next one is to be uju-cha, suhu-ju-cha, which means to be upright, really upright.

70
00:06:58,127 --> 00:06:59,427
So this is to do with

71
00:06:59,745 --> 00:07:11,197
you know, our moral rectitude, you know, and to sort of get away from the stuff that comes out of delusion, of acquisitiveness, aversion and fear.

72
00:07:12,680 --> 00:07:16,663
The next one is suvaco, which means skillful speech when spoken.

73
00:07:17,644 --> 00:07:27,175
So it's to be, the speech has to be kindly, it has to be truthful, beneficial, and rather importantly, timely, right?

74
00:07:27,194 --> 00:07:27,254
So,

75
00:07:28,146 --> 00:07:32,334
It might be kind, truthful and beneficial, but you shouldn't have said it then.

76
00:07:34,257 --> 00:07:39,447
Moodoo is a softness, a tenderness, and it's normally put with the word for heart.

77
00:07:39,949 --> 00:07:43,394
So it's a gentle heart, a tender heart, a gentle person.

78
00:07:44,958 --> 00:07:52,011
And Atimani is to be without pride, arrogance, conceit, to be sort of unpretentious.

79
00:07:54,826 --> 00:07:57,809
So those are sort of virtues that we need to develop.

80
00:07:58,370 --> 00:07:59,391
And then he carries on.

81
00:07:59,511 --> 00:08:05,156
Now, the next verse, he says, to be content, santusako, to be contented.

82
00:08:05,456 --> 00:08:15,927
Now, this isn't the contentment that you get when you've done a good job and you feel contented or you've found someone whom you like to be with and you feel contented.

83
00:08:15,947 --> 00:08:18,309
This contentment is a basic line.

84
00:08:18,389 --> 00:08:22,132
It's a sort of basic attitude of contentment.

85
00:08:22,636 --> 00:08:29,023
to enter each moment with that sort of sense of this will do, this contentment.

86
00:08:29,043 --> 00:08:38,133
It doesn't mean you can't change something, but it underlies everything that we do, a sense of contentment.

87
00:08:42,378 --> 00:08:46,042
The next one is subha, which means easily maintained.

88
00:08:46,662 --> 00:08:51,106
This actually probably refers to the monastics.

89
00:08:52,370 --> 00:09:02,186
But it's a case of making a distinction between what you need, what you want, and what is actually sufficient.

90
00:09:02,846 --> 00:09:07,575
And that will determine on whatever you have to do in your daily life.

91
00:09:08,657 --> 00:09:14,145
But basically, it's really needing only little.

92
00:09:14,966 --> 00:09:18,613
And these days, of course, with climate change, it has a bit more meaning.

93
00:09:21,596 --> 00:09:24,621
The next one is apaki cho, which means to be less busy.

94
00:09:24,642 --> 00:09:26,063
Well, I think that rings a bell, doesn't it?

95
00:09:26,323 --> 00:09:33,875
We're always doing just trying to do too much, trying to achieve too much, you know, burnout and all that sort of stuff.

96
00:09:35,197 --> 00:09:42,710
So it's good to reflect upon our lifestyle, just, you know, find out where we're actually stressing and to just let go of a few things.

97
00:09:42,850 --> 00:09:44,753
I think it's to do with priority, you know.

98
00:09:47,145 --> 00:09:54,714
And there's also, I think what also helps in life is to make the small tasks that we do meaningful.

99
00:09:55,815 --> 00:09:59,158
Just, you know, washing pots, vacuuming and all that sort of stuff.

100
00:09:59,178 --> 00:10:02,341
Normally, we want to get them out of the way, you know, and get on with life.

101
00:10:04,063 --> 00:10:14,335
But if you see them as an occasion where you can just stop for a minute and do them very mindfully in a very relaxed way, you know, abandoning all ill will and

102
00:10:14,533 --> 00:10:20,527
They become little islands, you see, and then from there you launch into your next project.

103
00:10:21,809 --> 00:10:25,739
So remember the old Zen saying, when you wash the pots, just wash the pots.

104
00:10:27,842 --> 00:10:33,976
Engaging lightly, salahuka vuti, salahuka vuti.

105
00:10:34,462 --> 00:10:38,787
No, this is not to take things too serious, you know, to keep mindfulness.

106
00:10:40,207 --> 00:10:45,793
Not to be able to relax and to have that wholesome heart attitude.

107
00:10:46,193 --> 00:10:49,015
It's actually, you know, just to keep a smile on the face.

108
00:10:49,056 --> 00:10:54,480
The background smile really helps, you know, so you don't get too serious about things.

109
00:10:55,883 --> 00:10:58,465
Sant'Indrio, this is quietening the faculties.

110
00:10:58,565 --> 00:11:01,888
So, you know, we're a very visual society.

111
00:11:02,172 --> 00:11:21,008
uh culture you know with all this um uh youtube and tv and netflix and and social media and um and we're always looking for some sort of uh sensual delight you know food

112
00:11:21,325 --> 00:11:22,645
the countryside.

113
00:11:22,806 --> 00:11:26,249
So we're always looking for that sort of excitement.

114
00:11:27,009 --> 00:11:31,133
And in a sense, that misses the mark because it's not quite a happiness, right?

115
00:11:31,153 --> 00:11:34,515
And that's why often excitement doesn't work for us.

116
00:11:34,937 --> 00:11:38,919
Whatever used to make us really excited, you know, loses its flavor.

117
00:11:39,379 --> 00:11:42,383
So it is a case of, you know, being more content.

118
00:11:42,462 --> 00:11:44,845
It sort of comes back to being content.

119
00:11:45,666 --> 00:11:50,590
And to just every so often to spend some time just looking at a blank wall is...

120
00:11:51,750 --> 00:11:55,315
And just allowing that sense to calm down a bit, you know.

121
00:11:55,375 --> 00:12:04,125
Nipako just means prudent, wise, discreet, thoughtful.

122
00:12:04,386 --> 00:12:06,428
So that's a lovely quality, isn't it?

123
00:12:06,889 --> 00:12:11,535
To be considerate, basically, to be considerate, to be aware of what other people need.

124
00:12:12,015 --> 00:12:14,119
We're always centering upon ourselves.

125
00:12:15,299 --> 00:12:19,125
Apagabo means to be modest, to be courteous and not impudent.

126
00:12:19,426 --> 00:12:23,611
So again, it's about not pushing yourself.

127
00:12:24,552 --> 00:12:32,024
I mean, the word humility doesn't go down too well these days because we all believe in the sovereign self, you know.

128
00:12:33,085 --> 00:12:44,741
But humility actually just means to, you know, to be natural and to be in communication with people, to see yourself in relationship, you know.

129
00:12:45,784 --> 00:12:51,734
Well, this is, again, a reinforcement not to hanker after worldly things.

130
00:12:52,715 --> 00:13:07,636
So, you know, it's like when you walk down the shopping mall or something like that, and your eyes constantly gazing at things, you know, the clothes, the jewelry, the computer, the laptops, you know, the phones.

131
00:13:08,418 --> 00:13:11,423
It's always looking for something, you know.

132
00:13:11,442 --> 00:13:15,589
But if you're there to get something specific, you know, just go for it.

133
00:13:17,019 --> 00:13:18,120
and then have a cup of tea.

134
00:13:20,783 --> 00:13:30,092
So all this is about, you know, calming the senses, you know, just calming down, trying to be much more contented.

135
00:13:31,514 --> 00:13:35,457
The third stanza, so he sums it all up here.

136
00:13:35,477 --> 00:13:41,144
He says not to commit even the slightest deeds that a wise person could find fault with.

137
00:13:41,163 --> 00:13:43,686
So that basically sums it up, yeah?

138
00:13:44,121 --> 00:13:48,206
Now, this wise person is the spiritual friend, your Kalyanamita.

139
00:13:48,767 --> 00:13:50,028
That could be a teacher.

140
00:13:50,048 --> 00:13:56,774
It could be a very close friend, somebody whom you can talk to about things which have a spiritual meaning.

141
00:13:57,515 --> 00:14:01,299
And if there isn't one, you know, there's always the Buddha within.

142
00:14:01,360 --> 00:14:13,032
I mean, when I have a moral question or, in a sense, any question, you know, if I just sit very still and just ask this Buddha within, just plunk the question into the heart,

143
00:14:13,552 --> 00:14:15,938
Yeah, I normally get a fairly good answer, you know.

144
00:14:18,264 --> 00:14:28,572
So we have a sort of a wisdom inside us, you know, but often sometimes, of course, we're overcome with doubt and to discuss it with somebody can be very helpful.

145
00:14:30,038 --> 00:14:32,941
And then we get the first well-wishing.

146
00:14:33,041 --> 00:14:39,288
So, may all beings live in safety, kemino, and in gladness, suki, sukinos.

147
00:14:39,307 --> 00:14:41,470
The word suki just means happy.

148
00:14:41,870 --> 00:14:45,072
And if you put a D instead, it's duki, that means you're not happy.

149
00:14:47,235 --> 00:14:50,399
And then it says, sabesata bawantu sukitata.

150
00:14:50,739 --> 00:14:55,403
So, may all beings develop, may become more happy, right?

151
00:14:55,423 --> 00:14:59,168
So, that's your first thing, is giving us a hint as to what we ought to say.

152
00:15:02,876 --> 00:15:05,220
And it's not about me feeling bad.

153
00:15:05,259 --> 00:15:08,102
Well, when you're doing the method, it's not about making yourself feel happy.

154
00:15:09,264 --> 00:15:10,566
Your intention is about others.

155
00:15:10,885 --> 00:15:14,690
I mean, there is a point where you turn into yourself and say, may I be happy?

156
00:15:14,870 --> 00:15:16,351
There's no problem with that.

157
00:15:16,831 --> 00:15:19,596
But you're not practicing metta in order to be happy.

158
00:15:19,995 --> 00:15:22,818
Then it just becomes a self-centered practice.

159
00:15:22,839 --> 00:15:29,807
You're doing it in order to establish a relationship with the world, which is one of giving, of offering.

160
00:15:30,707 --> 00:15:30,807
Yeah.

161
00:15:32,830 --> 00:15:39,758
And then he gives us ways in which we can do this, gives us a technique.

162
00:15:40,177 --> 00:15:50,309
So he says, whatever beings there are, weak or strong, without exception, long or short, big, medium-sized, small, subtle or gross.

163
00:15:50,890 --> 00:15:54,475
Now the word here is pana, which means breathing beings.

164
00:15:55,936 --> 00:16:01,722
So I presume this includes insects, but I'm not so sure about bacteria, if they're beings.

165
00:16:02,311 --> 00:16:10,981
And what he's suggesting is no matter how a being looks, it's always that attitude of offering goodwill.

166
00:16:14,125 --> 00:16:17,028
Doesn't matter what their physical shape is.

167
00:16:19,711 --> 00:16:22,576
In the second verse, he sort of opens it out.

168
00:16:22,635 --> 00:16:28,722
He says to those who are visible or invisible, can't even see them.

169
00:16:29,006 --> 00:16:36,099
residing near or far, those who have already been born and those who've yet to be born.

170
00:16:36,119 --> 00:16:39,644
This is almost sort of transcending space and time, okay?

171
00:16:40,186 --> 00:16:42,951
So, you're really sort of just expanding it outwards.

172
00:16:47,398 --> 00:16:49,682
Now, in the sixth verse,

173
00:16:55,417 --> 00:17:05,095
It's, let no one, now he's come back to, well, once you've developed this meta, you can't do this sort of thing.

174
00:17:05,115 --> 00:17:07,018
You can't deceive somebody.

175
00:17:07,659 --> 00:17:11,425
So to deceive somebody really is to take advantage of them, you know.

176
00:17:13,148 --> 00:17:14,972
And let me see, I've lost my place here.

177
00:17:15,473 --> 00:17:17,356
Nanga, let him wish no harm.

178
00:17:19,260 --> 00:17:21,624
Yeah, not to take advantage of somebody.

179
00:17:22,045 --> 00:17:26,069
And then the next one is not to despise anybody, right?

180
00:17:26,089 --> 00:17:28,413
So you have to be careful about that.

181
00:17:29,315 --> 00:17:32,979
Not to be excessively, not to be angrily critical.

182
00:17:33,901 --> 00:17:36,584
You've got to watch out for jealousy and bad mouthing.

183
00:17:38,886 --> 00:17:42,372
And of course, this also refers to ourselves, you know, what they call the inner critic.

184
00:17:42,392 --> 00:17:45,336
You know, when you hear yourself lambasting yourself, it's just...

185
00:17:45,906 --> 00:17:48,832
You know, just turn towards it and say, calm down.

186
00:17:48,893 --> 00:17:52,859
You know, you have to turn it into a little devil and give it a hug.

187
00:17:56,246 --> 00:17:58,510
So again, it's not wishing harm to anyone.

188
00:17:58,530 --> 00:18:01,936
He sums it up with that, not wishing harm to anyone.

189
00:18:04,442 --> 00:18:05,703
And in the seventh verse.

190
00:18:07,085 --> 00:18:17,005
He points out, just as a mother would protect her only child at the risk of her own life, even so we should cultivate boundless thoughts of loving kindness towards all beings.

191
00:18:17,665 --> 00:18:23,136
Now, that's a very strong image, a mother protecting a child who's being threatened.

192
00:18:23,919 --> 00:18:26,123
And I saw a video recently.

193
00:18:26,710 --> 00:18:49,393
of a lion and a lioness who were beginning to mate and they were walking at opposite sides of a uh of a fence that was obviously a containment in a in a reservation for them and as the lion moved uh down one side of the fence he was sort of giving sounds of yawning if you can imagine that like a

194
00:18:51,262 --> 00:18:53,886
like a lion yawning.

195
00:18:54,188 --> 00:18:59,615
And she, the lioness, was coming the other way with a companion, yawning as well, you see.

196
00:19:00,116 --> 00:19:04,284
So I thought when they get together, there'd be a bit of anky-panky and smooching, you see.

197
00:19:04,304 --> 00:19:08,190
But in fact, as soon as he got close to her, he attacked her viciously.

198
00:19:08,711 --> 00:19:10,773
And both of these lionesses attacked him.

199
00:19:11,576 --> 00:19:13,218
And then he pulled away, you see.

200
00:19:13,238 --> 00:19:17,305
And I thought, well, that is so strange because there was no comment about it.

201
00:19:18,044 --> 00:19:25,553
But what happens is if a lioness has cubs by a particular lion, then the lion goes off.

202
00:19:25,573 --> 00:19:26,394
You know, he's done his bit.

203
00:19:27,394 --> 00:19:36,125
If a stray lion comes past, he'll try to kill all those cubs, mate with her so that she has his cubs.

204
00:19:37,106 --> 00:19:38,548
And she has to defend them.

205
00:19:38,568 --> 00:19:41,532
And, you know, sometimes she's actually killed.

206
00:19:41,853 --> 00:19:44,997
But most times she just comes away with bites and bruises.

207
00:19:45,500 --> 00:19:48,503
So what he was doing was testing her fierceness.

208
00:19:49,085 --> 00:19:54,133
And then in the video, the commentator says, and now he's showing respect.

209
00:19:55,315 --> 00:20:00,142
I couldn't work that out, but seemingly he was showing her respect.

210
00:20:03,386 --> 00:20:06,411
And of course, we have the story of the Buddha.

211
00:20:07,150 --> 00:20:15,702
whiting the elephant that had been set upon him by the dastardly Devadatta, who was a cousin and wanted to lead the order.

212
00:20:16,523 --> 00:20:17,806
He had lots of criticism.

213
00:20:18,606 --> 00:20:22,492
And that was the picture I had up before.

214
00:20:22,973 --> 00:20:27,200
Just in case you didn't see it, I'll just share the screen quickly.

215
00:20:30,144 --> 00:20:32,126
So that's the mudra.

216
00:20:32,647 --> 00:20:35,352
That's what we associate with it.

217
00:20:37,660 --> 00:20:40,723
with loving kindness, that hand, you see, offering it from love.

218
00:20:40,743 --> 00:20:44,568
It's nicely moved there.

219
00:20:44,588 --> 00:20:47,814
Normally, it's just a flat hand, which isn't so appealing.

220
00:20:48,314 --> 00:20:55,884
And in his lap, I'm taking that to be the Dharma, the jewel of the Dharma.

221
00:20:55,904 --> 00:21:01,010
It's a Thai statue, that.

222
00:21:01,030 --> 00:21:02,232
So now we have...

223
00:21:03,309 --> 00:21:12,944
A third way in which we can develop that metta, and it goes even further, let him cultivate a boundless thoughts of loving kindness towards the whole world.

224
00:21:13,484 --> 00:21:19,795
And what he means there is, of course, all the worlds, all the cosmos, above, below and all around.

225
00:21:20,236 --> 00:21:24,582
So that's that's that practice of doing it in the six directions.

226
00:21:24,843 --> 00:21:27,646
Normally, it's a compass thing, north, south and all that.

227
00:21:28,166 --> 00:21:32,352
And as we do it, all beings in front, behind, left, right, below and above.

228
00:21:32,912 --> 00:21:37,076
Unobstructed, free from hatred and enmity.

229
00:21:41,461 --> 00:21:50,051
Now, the next verse, he says, he's saying that this should be developed all the time.

230
00:21:50,152 --> 00:21:52,414
It should be just a natural state of mind.

231
00:21:52,494 --> 00:21:57,279
So whether you're standing, walking, seated or lying down, so as long as you're awake,

232
00:21:57,563 --> 00:21:59,345
You should develop this mindfulness.

233
00:21:59,846 --> 00:22:05,711
Now, whenever I read a translation, I always slip in affectionate there, right?

234
00:22:05,771 --> 00:22:07,074
It's not just mindfulness.

235
00:22:07,354 --> 00:22:08,976
It's an affectionate mindfulness.

236
00:22:09,675 --> 00:22:18,787
Now, just now, you see, as we're all looking at each other, just put a little kindling of kindness in your heart towards everybody.

237
00:22:19,227 --> 00:22:21,890
See, you can do it, can't you?

238
00:22:21,910 --> 00:22:27,215
See, that can be there all the time, even when we're not so aware of it.

239
00:22:27,938 --> 00:22:29,461
And that's what he's asking us to do.

240
00:22:29,721 --> 00:22:32,367
And he calls it a divine abiding.

241
00:22:32,468 --> 00:22:34,692
So this is like being a God.

242
00:22:38,321 --> 00:22:40,767
And in the final verse...

243
00:22:41,438 --> 00:22:42,299
He sums it up.

244
00:22:42,339 --> 00:22:45,746
He says, you don't want to have erroneous views.

245
00:22:45,945 --> 00:23:01,476
So these are the views about how we create suffering for ourselves through that wrong desire, understanding impermanence, and the fact that we have to get used to the idea that we're going to grow old, sick, and die.

246
00:23:02,778 --> 00:23:04,340
And this...

247
00:23:04,809 --> 00:23:09,675
This relationship we have with the body, heart, and mind of it being me, right?

248
00:23:09,756 --> 00:23:13,461
So that's the identity of having this human form.

249
00:23:14,021 --> 00:23:16,805
And our practice of vipassana is trying to make that clear.

250
00:23:17,306 --> 00:23:25,115
And in fact, what we are looking for is what's looking, right?

251
00:23:25,757 --> 00:23:29,821
There's also Rona's views about karma, you know, that you can't get away with anything.

252
00:23:30,303 --> 00:23:31,964
It comes back in one way or the other.

253
00:23:32,603 --> 00:23:36,469
There's a very interesting quote from Jung that I came across.

254
00:23:36,788 --> 00:23:41,715
He says, whatever has been repressed will manifest as fate.

255
00:23:43,077 --> 00:23:58,981
And if you look at your life and you find yourself doing something over and over again, falling into the same sort of mistake, then underneath that, there will be some sort of suppressed or repressed mental state.

256
00:24:00,633 --> 00:24:02,798
I think that's really quite an insight.

257
00:24:03,861 --> 00:24:08,311
So then endowed with these virtues and wise with insight.

258
00:24:09,394 --> 00:24:12,943
Now, the next line is a bit heavy because you have to abandon all sensual desire.

259
00:24:13,285 --> 00:24:16,633
But remember, it doesn't mean you stop eating.

260
00:24:16,883 --> 00:24:19,945
It just means to abandon the wrong desire, right?

261
00:24:20,007 --> 00:24:27,674
Which is that greed, which is trying to get happiness from the sensual world as a permanent thing.

262
00:24:27,815 --> 00:24:28,635
That's the problem.

263
00:24:29,156 --> 00:24:31,839
Happiness arises and passes away like anything else.

264
00:24:34,563 --> 00:24:37,385
And then he says, you don't have to be reborn again.

265
00:24:37,705 --> 00:24:40,789
The actual translation is not to be conceived in a womb.

266
00:24:41,790 --> 00:24:43,633
Basically, you don't have to be reborn again.

267
00:24:44,086 --> 00:24:50,573
So that's just a quick run through this particular discourse.

268
00:24:50,593 --> 00:24:52,474
So, OK, so how do we practice it?

269
00:24:52,755 --> 00:24:55,438
Well, remember that it's good to have a touchstone.

270
00:24:55,478 --> 00:25:02,325
It's good to have something you can go back to, which raises that sense of warmth, that kindling in the heart.

271
00:25:03,165 --> 00:25:07,490
So, for instance, I know one teacher talks about holding a baby.

272
00:25:07,529 --> 00:25:10,673
You use a pet.

273
00:25:11,253 --> 00:25:12,996
Yeah, we always love pets.

274
00:25:14,630 --> 00:25:39,692
um or some uh we normally start with the benefactor so that's somebody who warms the heart you see now if you've got that and you've developed it a bit you can always go back to it whenever we move into a category and you don't feel you don't you feel that the warmth in the heart has gone you just go back and remind yourself of that kindling by bringing that person or the pet or whatever it is to mind

275
00:25:41,005 --> 00:25:47,351
And remember that you're developing it in order to develop right attitude towards all beings.

276
00:25:50,795 --> 00:25:54,258
And the other thing is not to worry if it doesn't come, see?

277
00:25:54,278 --> 00:25:56,961
Because the heart has its own logic, doesn't it?

278
00:25:57,621 --> 00:25:59,663
You want to feel loving, you're just not feeling it.

279
00:26:00,903 --> 00:26:05,128
So if you obsess about that, then it becomes a misery.

280
00:26:06,369 --> 00:26:08,511
But just by doing the practice, I think you'll find.

281
00:26:09,132 --> 00:26:09,712
Now, I...

282
00:26:09,894 --> 00:26:15,161
I have a poet, General Manly Hopkins, who some of you might know.

283
00:26:15,221 --> 00:26:18,325
He's known as the father of modern English poetry.

284
00:26:19,445 --> 00:26:27,095
And some of his sonnets are really about his own spiritual development.

285
00:26:27,115 --> 00:26:33,082
And there's one that starts, My own heart, let me more have pity on.

286
00:26:33,923 --> 00:26:38,248
Let me live to my sad self, hereafter kind, charitable.

287
00:26:38,936 --> 00:26:44,222
Not live this tormented mind with this tormented mind tormenting yet.

288
00:26:45,044 --> 00:26:46,384
I cast for comfort.

289
00:26:47,026 --> 00:26:58,317
I can no more get by groping round my comfortless than blind eyes in their darkened day or thirst confined thirsts all in all, in all the world of wet.

290
00:26:59,179 --> 00:27:06,125
So those first two lines I've often used, you know, my own heart let me more have pity, you know.

291
00:27:06,612 --> 00:27:11,698
And if you can get that kindling within yourself, then you offer it out from there.

292
00:27:12,419 --> 00:27:14,000
I find it extremely strong.

293
00:27:15,163 --> 00:27:22,151
Let me live to my sad self hereafter, kind and charitable, to my anxious self, my angry self, to my guilty self, you see.

294
00:27:22,352 --> 00:27:30,721
It doesn't do much for the poem, but you can use it that way so that you can generate a warmth towards yourself.

295
00:27:30,741 --> 00:27:31,522
And of course...

296
00:27:32,296 --> 00:27:34,818
It's easier to move from that heart.

297
00:27:34,838 --> 00:27:41,807
But as I say, if it's not there, not to worry at all, you can use your pet or something to generate it.

298
00:27:42,607 --> 00:27:45,471
Okay.

299
00:27:45,491 --> 00:27:45,971
Very good.

300
00:27:46,472 --> 00:27:55,284
So I thought what we would do is instead of usually ending with the refuge and precepts, we would start with those.

301
00:27:56,105 --> 00:27:58,907
And then I would do that guidance through the Metta Sutta.

302
00:27:59,689 --> 00:28:02,251
And then we would continue until the end.

303
00:28:02,569 --> 00:28:14,824
when I would read the discourse, a translation of the discourse, and end off with our usual chant of Sabe Sata Sukhita Hantu.

304
00:28:19,329 --> 00:28:19,650
Okay.

305
00:28:20,550 --> 00:28:32,424
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and that by your practice of metta, you will generate a beautiful heart that will lead you to everlasting peace and happiness.

